 Center Turns 20 Today|first=Mike|last=Swift|url=http://articles.courant.com/1995-01-09/news/9501090021_1_civic-pride-main-street-hartford-civic-center|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=January 9, 1995|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref><br>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|30000000|1975}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})\n| architect           = [[KlingStubbins|Kling & Associates]]<br>Danos and Associates<ref>{{cite book |title=Modern concrete: Volume 40|year=1976|publisher=Pit & Quarry Publications|location=Chicago|page=20}}</ref>\n| project_manager     = [[Gilbane|Gilbane Building Company]]<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |title=XL Center|url=http://www.emporis.com/application/?lng=3&nav=building&id=261572|publisher=Emporis|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = Fraoli, Blum, and Yesselman, Engineers<ref>{{cite web|title=Failure Cases - Hartford Civic Center |url=http://matdl.org/failurecases/Building%20Cases/Hartford.htm |publisher=Materials Education and Research Pathway |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801103558/http://matdl.org/failurecases/Building%20Cases/Hartford.htm |archivedate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = William L. Crow Construction Company<ref name=\"emporis\"/>\n| tenants             = [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (1997\u20132010, 2013&ndash;present)<br>[[UConn Huskies]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]])<br> [[UConn Huskies men's basketball|Men's Basketball]] (1975\u20131978, 1980\u2013present, part time)<br>[[UConn Huskies women's basketball|Women's Basketball]] (1975\u20131978, 1980\u2013present, part time)<br> [[UConn Huskies men's ice hockey|Men's Ice Hockey]] (2013&ndash;present)<br>[[Hartford Whalers|New England / Hartford Whalers]] ([[World Hockey Association|WHA]] / [[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1975\u20131978, 1980\u20131997)<br>[[Connecticut Coyotes]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (1995\u20131996)<br>[[New England Blizzard]] ([[American Basketball League (1996\u20131998)|ABL]]) (1996\u20131998)<br>[[New England Sea Wolves]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (1999\u20132000)<br>[[Boston Celtics]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1975\u20131995, part time)<br>[[Hartford Hellions]] ([[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|MISL]]) (1980\u20131981)<br>[[Connecticut Pride|Hartford Hellcats / Connecticut Pride]] ([[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]]) (199?&ndash;2000)<br>[[Hartford Wolf Pack|Connecticut Whale]] (AHL) (2010&ndash;2013)\n| seating_capacity    = Concerts: 16,500<br>Basketball: 15,600<br>Ice hockey: 14,750 (9,801 with curtain system)\n| website             = [http://www.xlcenter.com/ Official Website]\n}}\n\nThe '''XL Center''' (originally known as the '''Hartford Civic Center''') is a multi-purpose [[arena]] and [[convention center]] located in downtown [[Hartford, Connecticut]].  It is owned by the City of Hartford and operated by [[Comcast Spectacor#Global Spectrum|Spectra]].  In December 2007, the Center was renamed when the arena's naming rights were sold to [[XL Group]] insurance company in a 6-year agreement.  The arena is ranked the 28th largest among college basketball arenas.  Opened in 1974 as the Hartford Civic Center and originally located adjacent to [[Civic Center Mall]], which was demolished in 2004. It consists of two facilities: the Veterans Memorial Coliseum and the Exhibition Center.\n\nOn March 21, 2007, the Capital Region Development Authority (CRDA) selected the Northland/[[Anschutz Entertainment Group]] proposal.  It was revealed that Northland will assume total responsibility for the building paying for any and all losses, and will keep any profits.  In 2012, the CRDA, put the contract out to bid with hopes of combining the operations with [[Pratt & Whitney Stadium at Rentschler Field|Rentschler Field]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Secrecy On XL Center, Rentschler Plans Isn't Helping Matters|first=Jeff|last=Jacobs|url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-02-03/sports/hc-jacobs-column-0204-20130203_1_crda-board-capital-region-development-authority-bids|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=February 3, 2013|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref> In February 2013, [[Comcast Spectacor#Global Spectrum|Global Spectrum]] of Philadelphia, was chosen to take over both the XL Center and Rentschler Field<ref>{{cite news |title=Philadelphia Group Picked To Run XL Center, Rentschler Field|first=Kenneth R.|last=Gosselin|url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-02-07/business/hc-xl-center-rentschler-decision-20130207_1_capital-improvements-aeg-management-ct-bushnell-management-services|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=February 7, 2013|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref> with Ovations Food Services taking over all food and beverage operations.\n\n==Hartford Civic Center==\nThe Civic Center is the full-time home of the [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] AHL hockey team and part-time home of the [[University of Connecticut]] (UConn) men's and women's basketball teams and the [[UConn Huskies men's ice hockey]] team.  Starting in the late 1990s, UConn men's basketball moved most of their important games&mdash;including the bulk of their [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] games&mdash;to the Coliseum.   During the 2011\u20132012 season, for instance, they played 11 home games at the Coliseum and only eight at their on-campus facility, [[Harry A. Gampel Pavilion|Gampel Pavilion]].  This practice continued when the Huskies joined the [[American Athletic Conference]], [[2010\u201313 Big East Conference realignment|successor]] to the original Big East, in 2013. The [[Connecticut Huskies men's ice hockey|UConn men's hockey team]] uses the XL Center as its primary home as the newest men's member of [[Hockey East]].<!--UConn is still the newest men's member of Hockey East, but not the newest overall; that would be the Holy Cross women.-->\n\nIt was the home of the [[Hartford Whalers|New England/Hartford Whalers]] of the [[World Hockey Association|WHA]] and [[National Hockey League|NHL]] from 1975 to 1978 and 1980 to 1997, and the [[Hartford Hellions]] of the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u20131992)|MISL]] from 1980 to 1981, and the [[New England Blizzard]] of the [[American Basketball League (1996\u20131998)|ABL]] from 1996 to 1998, and hosted occasional [[Boston Celtics]] home games from 1975 to 1995.  It was the home of the [[Connecticut Coyotes]] and later the [[New England Sea Wolves]] of the [[Arena Football League (1987\u20132008)|Arena Football League]].\n\nThe arena seats 15,635 for [[ice hockey]] and 16,294 for [[basketball]], 16,606 for center-stage [[concerts]], 16,282 for end-stage concerts, and 8,239 for \u00be-end stage concerts, and contains 46 luxury suites and a 310-seat Coliseum Club, plus {{convert|25000|sqft|m2|-2}} of arena floor space, enabling it to be used for trade shows and conventions in addition to concerts, circuses, ice shows, sporting events and other events.  The [[Commencement at CCSU|graduation ceremonies of Central Connecticut State University]] and other local colleges are also held annually at the XL Center.\n\n===Early history and roof collapse===\n[[File:HartfordCivicCenterSoldOut.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The arena remains a site for popular concerts. October 2007.]]\nAs originally built in 1975, it seated 10,507 for hockey, and served as the home of the then&ndash;[[New England Whalers]] for three years. In the early morning of January 18, 1978, the weight of snow from the day's heavy snowstorm caused the Civic Center's roof to collapse. Engineering analyses during litigation following the collapse indicated that compression members were overloaded through undersizing and underestimation of the probable loadings, and that lateral bracing of individual members was insufficient. Investigations attributed the design issues to the unprecedented use of and trust in computer analysis. An absence of peer review for the novel structure and design process, and fragmentation of oversight responsibility during construction were also cited as contributing factors. Evidence showed that the roof had started to fail during construction, with bowed compression members. These distortions, and an unpredicted degree of deflection in the structure, were not investigated before the collapse.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hartford Civic Center Arena Roof Collapse|first=Rachel|last=Martin|url=http://www.eng.uab.edu/cee/faculty/ndelatte/case_studies_project/Hartford%20Civic%20Center/hartford.htm|publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham|accessdate=November 20, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108024915/http://www.eng.uab.edu/cee/faculty/ndelatte/case_studies_project/Hartford%20Civic%20Center/hartford.htm|archivedate=January 8, 2008}}</ref> There were no injuries due to the collapse. The building was heavily renovated and re-opened January 17, 1980.\n\nThe Arena hosted the [[Hartford Whalers]] from January 11, 1980 to April 13, 1997. Shortly thereafter the team relocated to [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] to become the [[Carolina Hurricanes]]. In 1994, new owner [[Peter Karmanos]] purchased the team and pledged to keep the Whalers in Connecticut until 1998, unless they could not sell over 11,000 season tickets. After failed negotiations to build a new downtown arena for the Whalers with then-Governor [[John G. Rowland]], on March 25, 1997, Karmanos announced that the team would leave. The [[New York Rangers]], looking to capitalize on Hartford as a potential market, placed its farm team there to become the Hartford Wolf Pack starting in 1997. After a short stint as the [[Connecticut Whale (AHL)|Connecticut Whale]], they reverted to the Wolf Pack moniker in 2013. Renovations were complete in October 2014, which is set to serve the arena until its fiftieth birthday.\n\n===Current arena and recent renovations===\nIn September 2010, the arena was upgraded with a new center-hung scoreboard with four Sony Jumbotrons and a state-of-the-art sound system.<ref>{{cite news |title=XL Center Gets New Video Boards|first=Jeff|last=Jacobs|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-10-05/sports/hc-xl-scoreboard-20101005_1_video-boards-video-screens-aeg|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=October 5, 2010|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\nThe Connecticut State Legislature set aside $35 million in funding for improvements to the XL Center that began in early spring 2014 and completed in time for the start of the 2014-15 seasons of the Wolf Pack and UConn men's hockey in October. Improvements included upgrades to the mechanical system, locker rooms and concourse, replacing jumbotrons with a new [[high-definition video|HD video]] board, as well as aesthetic improvements such as a new bar area inside the arena and luxury seating in the lower bowl. A portion of the $35 million allocation went  towards a study on the arena's long-term viability; either more major renovations or replacing it with a new facility.\n\n==Events==\nThe XL Center has held many notable events including:\n[[File:Hartfordmj.jpg|thumb|200px|The Veterans Memorial Coliseum as set up for [[Monster Jam]].]]\n\n*The [[ECAC Men's Basketball Tournaments|ECAC New England Region Tournament]], a [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] men's [[college basketball]] tournament organized by the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]] (ECAC), took place at the Hartford Civic Center on March 3 and 5, [[ECAC Men's Basketball Tournaments#1977 Tournaments|1977]]. The tournament champion received an automatic bid to the [[1977 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ECAC Men's Basketball Tournaments|url=http://jonfmorse.com/wiki/index.php?title=ECAC_Men%27s_Basketball_Tournaments|work=Varsity Pride|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1977 ECAC Men's Basketball Tournaments|url=http://jonfmorse.com/wiki/index.php?title=1977_ECAC_Men%27s_Basketball_Tournaments|work=Varsity Pride|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*The 1982 [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] and 1988\u20131990 [[America East Conference]] men's basketball tournaments were also here, as well as occasional games of the [[UConn Huskies]] [[UConn Huskies men's basketball|men's basketball team]].<ref name=\"XL Center\">{{cite web |title=XL Center (Hartford, CT)|url=http://www.uconnhuskies.com/facilities/xl-center.html|publisher=University of Connecticut Department of Athletics|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n* Rock group the [[Grateful Dead]] performed a two-night stand at the arena on October 14 and 15, 1983. The concert from October 14 was released in its entirety on the 1996 live album ''[[Dick's Picks Volume 6]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Catlin |first1=Roger |title='83 Hartford Show Latest \"Dick's Pick\" |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1996-11-03-9611010049-story.html |website=courant.com |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n*The PBR ([[Professional Bull Riders]]) made their first-ever visit to the XL Center for a Built Ford Tough Series (now known as the Unleash the Beast Series) event the weekend of October 7\u20139, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=PBR Built Ford Tough Series Visits Hartford for First Time|first=Sara|last=Broun|url=http://www.pbr.com/en/news/press-releases/2011/10/pbr-visits-hartford.aspx|publisher=Professional Bull Riders|date=October 6, 2011|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*The arena hosted the Kellogg's Tour of Gymnastics Champions in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Kellogg's Tour of Gymnastics Champions takes center stage beginning Sept. 15|url=https://usagym.org/pages/post.html?PostID=19213|publisher=usagym.org|accessdate=April 1, 2019}}</ref>\n*The arena has hosted many professional wrestling events; including [[Survivor Series (1990)|1990 Survivor Series]], [[WrestleMania XI]], [[No Way Out (2000)|2000 No Way Out]], [[Vengeance (2004)|2004 Vengeance]], and [[Money in the Bank (2019)|2019 Money in the Bank]].\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Basketball\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Boston Celtics}}\"|Years\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Boston Celtics}}\"|Capacity\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Boston Celtics}}\"|1975\u20131979\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">11,000</div> \n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Boston Celtics}}\"|1979\u20131987\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">15,134</div>  \n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Boston Celtics}}\"|1987\u20131989\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">16,016</div> \n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Boston Celtics}}\"|1989\u20132014\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">16,294</div> \n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Boston Celtics}}\"|2014\u2013present \n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">15,564</div>  \n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Hockey\n|-\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-top:#00008b 5px solid; border-bottom:#E3393F 5px solid;\"|Years\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-top:#00008b 5px solid; border-bottom:#E3393F 5px solid;\"|Capacity\n|-\n! style=\"background:#00008b; color:#FFFFFF;\"|1975\u20131979\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">10,507</div>\n|- \n! style=\"background:#E3393F; color:#FFFFFF;\"|1979\u20131980\n| 14,460<ref>{{cite web |title=1979-80 Hartford Whalers Results and Schedule|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/team_results.php?tid=46&sid=1980|publisher=Hockey Database|accessdate=February 27, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#00008b; color:#FFFFFF;\"|1980\u20131982\n| 14,510<ref>{{cite news |title=Duguay Gets 2 Goals As Rangers Win, 6-4|first=Deane|last=McGowen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/22/sports/duguay-gets-2-goals-as-rangers-win-6-4.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 22, 1981|accessdate=February 27, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#E3393F; color:#FFFFFF;\"|1983\u20131985\n| 14,817<ref>{{cite news |title=W