{"title_page": "St\u00e9phane Pasquier", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n'''St\u00e9phane Pasquier''' (born 17 January 1978) in [[Paris]], [[France]], is a [[flat racing]] [[jockey]]. In October 2006, he won the 85th [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]].\n\nHe began as an apprentice for the trainer [[Robert Collet]], and rode in his first race on 6 December 1994, on Raspoutine at [[Hippodrome de Saint-Cloud|Saint-Cloud Racecourse]]. His first victory was in his second race, riding Floris at [[Amiens]] racecourse on 9 September 1995.\n\nSt\u00e9phane Pasquier is a turbulent and strong character, and confesses to have lost his way in 1997, needing guidance from [[Robert Collet]] to help him back. Pasquier won his first Listed Race in 1999, then his first Group 3 race in May 2001, riding Acceleration in the [[Prix Corrida]].\n\nDuring the winter of 2001\u20132002, he rode in [[Singapore]] and on returning to France won his first Group 2 race, the [[Prix Greffulhe]]. His first ride in the [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]] followed in October 2002, finishing 8th on Fair Mix.\n\nAfter continued successes in Group races throughout 2003, in July 2004, his talent allowed him to join the prestigious [[Daniel Wildenstein]] stable as second jockey alongside the number one, [[Olivier Peslier]].\n\nOn 24 October 2004 he won the [[Prix Royal-Oak]], his first Group 1 race, with [[Westerner (horse)|Westerner]]. Several weeks later, he finished 4th in the [[Japan Cup]] aboard [[Policy Maker]].\n\nIn 2005, he won two Group 2 races (the [[Prix Maurice de Nieuil]] with Ostankino and the [[Grand Prix de Deauville]] with Marend), and finished 3rd in the [[Grosser Preis von Baden]], a Group 1, with [[Westerner (horse)|Westerner]].\n\nIn early 2006, everything was fine for St\u00e9phane Pasquier, winning a lot of races. But in the summer, he had a bizarre accident whilst watching the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] final, breaking a glass in his hands when [[David Trezeguet]]'s penalty shot hit the crossbar. The injury was expected to keep him out of racing for two months, but his strong character helped him to come back sooner. In late August, he resumed racing, and soon started winning again. In October, he rode an outsider [[Rail Link (horse)|Rail Link]] in the [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]], and was a surprise winner.<ref name=\"RTE\">\"[http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/1001/arcdetriomphe.html Link shock Arc win]\", [[RT\u00c9]], 1 October 2006, retrieved 2010-10-09</ref>\n\nIn 2007, St\u00e9phane Pasquier is awarded his first [[French flat racing Champion Jockey|Cravache d'Or]], riding 185 winners in the season.\n\nOn 2 May 2010 he rode the winner of the English [[1000 Guineas]] when [[Special Duty]] trained by [[Criquette Head-Maarek]] was awarded the race following a [[stewards' enquiry]].\n\nOn 1 Nov 2014 he rode Karakontie for Jonathan Pease to win the Breeders Cup Mile (GI) at Santa Anita Park (US)\n\n==Major wins==\n{{flagicon|France}} '''[[France]]'''\n* [[Crit\u00e9rium International (horse race)|Crit\u00e9rium International]] - (1) - Thewayyouare (2007)\n* [[Crit\u00e9rium de Saint-Cloud]] - (1) - Wonderment (2018)\n* [[Grand Prix de Paris]] - (2) - [[Zambezi Sun]] (2007), Erupt (2015)\n* [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]] - (1) - [[Rail Link (horse)|Rail Link]] (2006)\n* [[Prix de la For\u00eat]] - (2) - Toylsome (2007), Varenar (2009)\n* [[Prix de Diane]] - (1) - Senga (2017)\n* [[Poule d'Essai des Poulains]] - (2) - Lucayan (2012), [[Karakontie]] (2014)\n* [[Poule d'Essai des Pouliches]] - (1) - [[Special Duty]] (2010)\n* [[Prix d'Ispahan]] - (1) - [[Manduro]] (2007)\n* [[Prix du Jockey Club]] - (1) - [[Study of Man]] (2018)\n* [[Prix Jacques Le Marois]] - (1) - Manduro (2007)\n* [[Prix Jean-Luc Lagard\u00e8re]] - (1) - Karakontie (2013)\n* [[Prix Marcel Boussac]] - (1) - Proportional (2008)\n* [[Prix Maurice de Gheest]] - (1) - Signs of Blessing (2016)\n* [[Prix Royal-Oak]] - (1) - Westerner (2004)\n----\n{{flagicon|Canada}} '''Canada'''\n* [[Canadian International Stakes]] - (1) - Erupt (2016)\n----\n{{flagicon|Great Britain}} '''[[Great Britain]]'''\n* [[1,000 Guineas Stakes]] - Special Duty (2010)\n* [[Cheveley Park Stakes]] - (1) - Special Duty (2009)\n* [[Prince of Wales's Stakes]] - (1) - Manduro (2007)\n* [[Haydock Sprint Cup|Sprint Cup]] - (1) - African Rose (2008)\n----\n{{flagicon|Italy}} '''Italy'''\n* [[Gran Criterium]] - Law Enforcement (2012)\n----\n{{flagicon|United States}} '''United States'''\n* [[Breeders' Cup Mile]] - Karakontie (2014)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jockeys]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pasquier, Stephane}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French jockeys]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n'''St\u00e9phane Pasquier''' (born 17 January 1978) in [[Paris]], [[France]], is a [[flat racing]] [[jockey]]. In October 2006, he won the 85th [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]].\n\nHe began as an apprentice for the trainer [[Robert Collet]], and rode in his first race on 6 December 1994, on Raspoutine at [[Hippodrome de Saint-Cloud|Saint-Cloud Racecourse]]. His first victory was in his second race, riding Floris at [[Amiens]] racecourse on 9 September 1995.\n\nSt\u00e9phane Pasquier is a turbulent and strong character, and confesses to have lost his way in 1997, needing guidance from [[Robert Collet]] to help him back. Pasquier won his first Listed Race in 1999, then his first Group 3 race in May 2001, riding Acceleration in the [[Prix Corrida]].\n\nDuring the winter of 2001-2002, he rode in [[Singapore]] and on returning to France won his first Group 2 race, the [[Prix Greffulhe]]. His first ride in the [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]] followed in October 2002, finishing 8th on Fair Mix.\n\nAfter continued successes in Group races throughout 2003, in July 2004, his talent allowed him to join the prestigious [[Daniel Wildenstein]] stable as second jockey alongside the number one, [[Olivier Peslier]].\n\nOn 24 October 2004 he won the [[Prix Royal-Oak]], his first Group 1 race, with [[Westerner (horse)|Westerner]]. Several weeks later, he finished 4th in the [[Japan Cup]] aboard [[Policy Maker]].\n\nIn 2005, he won two Group 2 races (the [[Prix Maurice de Nieuil]] with Ostankino and the [[Grand Prix de Deauville]] with Marend), and finished 3rd in the [[Grosser Preis von Baden]], a Group 1, with [[Westerner (horse)|Westerner]].\n\nIn early 2006, everything was fine for St\u00e9phane Pasquier, winning a lot of races. But in the summer, he had a bizarre accident whilst watching the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] final, breaking a glass in his hands when [[David Trezeguet]]'s penalty shot hit the crossbar. The injury was expected to keep him out of racing for two months, but his strong character helped him to come back sooner. In late August, he resumed racing, and soon started winning again. In October, he rode an outsider [[Rail Link (horse)|Rail Link]] in the [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]], and was a surprise winner.<ref name=\"RTE\">\"[http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/1001/arcdetriomphe.html Link shock Arc win]\", [[RT\u00c9]], 1 October 2006, retrieved 2010-10-09</ref>\n\nIn 2007, St\u00e9phane Pasquier is awarded his first [[French flat racing Champion Jockey|Cravache d'Or]], riding 185 winners in the season.\n\nOn 2 May 2010 he rode the winner of the English [[1000 Guineas]] when [[Special Duty]] trained by [[Criquette Head-Maarek]] was awarded the race following a [[stewards' enquiry]].\n\nOn 1 Nov 2014 he rode Karakontie for Jonathan Pease to win the Breeders Cup Mile (GI) at Santa Anita Park (US)\n\n==Major wins==\n{{flagicon|France}} '''[[France]]'''\n* [[Crit\u00e9rium International (horse race)|Crit\u00e9rium International]] - (1) - Thewayyouare (2007)\n* [[Crit\u00e9rium de Saint-Cloud]] - (1) - Wonderment (2018)\n* [[Grand Prix de Paris]] - (2) - [[Zambezi Sun]] (2007), Erupt (2015)\n* [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]] - (1) - [[Rail Link (horse)|Rail Link]] (2006)\n* [[Prix de la For\u00eat]] - (2) - Toylsome (2007), Varenar (2009)\n* [[Prix de Diane]] - (1) - Senga (2017)\n* [[Poule d'Essai des Poulains]] - (2) - Lucayan (2012), [[Karakontie]] (2014)\n* [[Poule d'Essai des Pouliches]] - (1) - [[Special Duty]] (2010)\n* [[Prix d'Ispahan]] - (1) - [[Manduro]] (2007)\n* [[Prix du Jockey Club]] - (1) - [[Study of Man]] (2018)\n* [[Prix Jacques Le Marois]] - (1) - Manduro (2007)\n* [[Prix Jean-Luc Lagard\u00e8re]] - (1) - Karakontie (2013)\n* [[Prix Marcel Boussac]] - (1) - Proportional (2008)\n* [[Prix Maurice de Gheest]] - (1) - Signs of Blessing (2016)\n* [[Prix Royal-Oak]] - (1) - Westerner (2004)\n----\n{{flagicon|Canada}} '''Canada'''\n* [[Canadian International Stakes]] - (1) - Erupt (2016)\n----\n{{flagicon|Great Britain}} '''[[Great Britain]]'''\n* [[1,000 Guineas Stakes]] - Special Duty (2010)\n* [[Cheveley Park Stakes]] - (1) - Special Duty (2009)\n* [[Prince of Wales's Stakes]] - (1) - Manduro (2007)\n* [[Haydock Sprint Cup|Sprint Cup]] - (1) - African Rose (2008)\n----\n{{flagicon|Italy}} '''Italy'''\n* [[Gran Criterium]] - Law Enforcement (2012)\n----\n{{flagicon|United States}} '''United States'''\n* [[Breeders' Cup Mile]] - Karakontie (2014)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jockeys]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pasquier, Stephane}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French jockeys]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2001-2002 \u2192 2001\u20132002", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St%C3%A9phane_Pasquier"}
{"title_page": "List of mosques in Pakistan", "text_new": "Being an Islamic country, [[Pakistan]] is home to thousands of mosques. Some of the mosques are quite famous because of their size, beauty, architecture and history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakiholic.com/15-most-amazing-beautiful-mosques-pakistan/|title=15 Most Amazing and Beautiful Mosques in Pakistan|date=5 October 2016|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> The following is a '''list of [[mosque]]s in [[Pakistan]]'''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!class=unsortable|Images\n!City<!--Please order mosques according to their city's place in the alphabet-->\n!Capacity of worshipers\n!Area(m\u00b2)\n!Built\n!class=unsortable|Remarks\n!class=unsortable|References\n|-\n\n|[[Abbasi Mosque]]\n|[[File:Early Morning view of Abbasi Mosque.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Bahawalpur]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|1000}}\n|\n| 1849\n|Built by [[Bahawal Khan V|Nawab Bahawal Khan]] located at [[Derawar Fort]].\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Abbasi Mosque at Derawar Fort |url=https://www.beautifulmosque.com/Abbasi-Mosque-in-Bahawalpur-Pakistan |website=Beautifulmosque.com |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Built in 1849\">{{cite web |title=Built by Nawab Bahawal Khan in 1849 |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1230706 |website=www.dawn.com |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1230706|title=9 historical Pakistani mosques that will transport you to another time|first=Interactive|last=Desk|date=10 January 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Al-Sadiq Mosque, Bahawalpur]]\n| [[File:The grand mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Bahawalpur]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Aqsa Mosque, Rabwah]]\n| [[File:Masjid_Aqsa_Eingangsbereich.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Rabwah]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|18,500}}\n| {{convert|1650|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1972\n| Largest Mosque of the [[Ahmadiyya Community]] in Pakistan. The design was said to be inspired by the [[Badshahi Mosque]].\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ahmadiyyamosque.blogspot.com/2015/01/masjid-e-aqsa-rabwah-pakistan.html|title=Masjid-e-Aqsa - Rabwah, Pakistan|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Amburiq Mosque]]\n| [[File:D 07-08 (51).jpg|160px]]\n| [[Shigar]], [[Gilgit Baltistan]]\n| {{nts|500}}\n| {{convert|63|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 14th Century\n| It is one of the oldest mosque in [[Baltistan]] and was built by [[Mir Sayyid Ali Hamadani|Sayed Ali Hamdani]]. It is also one of the most famous landmarks and a major tourist attraction in Baltistan.\n| <ref name=\"archnet\">[https://archnet.org/sites/5514 Amburq Mosque]</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Shahzad Bashir|title=Messianic Hopes and Mystical Visions: The N\u00e5urbakhsh\u00e5iya Between Medieval|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uom79HNFPGgC&pg=PA252&dq=chaqchan+mosque&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dHRuUaGEEsjYrQfFpYDABw&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=chaqchan%20mosque&f=false}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Badshahi Mosque]]\n| [[Image:Badshahi Mosque July 1 2005 pic32 by Ali Imran (1).jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|100,000}}\n| {{convert|25642|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1673\n| Second largest mosque in [[Pakistan]] and the fifth in the world; it was the largest mosque in the world from 1673 to 1986. The mosque is located west of [[Lahore Fort]] along the outskirts of the [[Walled City of Lahore]], and is widely considered to be one of Lahore's most iconic landmarks.\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Badshahi Mosque, Lahore |url=http://www.pakistantoursguide.com/badshahi-mosque.html |website=www.pakistantoursguide.com |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Routledge\">{{cite book|title=Medieval Islamic Civilization: An Encyclopedia|date=31 October 2005|publisher=Routledge|page=91|last1=Meri|first1=Joseph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Badshahi Masjid|url=http://archnet.org/sites/2741|website=Archnet|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ualberta.ca\">{{cite web|url=https