 AD, sixteen years after the conquest of Sindh, indicating the best-preserved example of the earliest mosques in the region. Ruins are still preserved in the city.\n|<ref name=Wesler>{{cite book|title=An Archaeology of Religion|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0761858454|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qSExw3tH1oC&pg=PA253|author=Kit W. Wesler|accessdate=8 September 2012|page=253|date=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Mosque of Banbhore|url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=14204|publisher=ArchNet|accessdate=8 September 2012|quote=... the Jami' Masjid of Banbhore is one of the earliest known mosques in the Indo-Pakistan subcontinent.}}</ref><ref name=Sindh>{{cite web|title=Banbhore Museum|url=http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|work=Culture Department|publisher=Govt. of Sindh|accessdate=3 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108165854/http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Mosque (Khudabad)]]\n|[[File:Main building of Jamia Masjid Khudabad.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Dadu District]], [[Sindh]]\n|{{nts|5000}}\n|\n|1700 - 1718\n| The mosque is situated in [[Khudabad]] in [[Dadu District]] and was built during the reign of [[Yar Muhammad Kalhoro]] between 1700 and 1718.\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamia Mosque (Khudabad) in Dadu District |url=https://www.sindhidunya.com/khudabad-mosque-antique-heritage-sindh/ |website=www.sindhidunya.com |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque|Jamia Al-Kauthar]]\n|[[File:Jamia Al Kauthar Mosque.png|160px]]\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|{{nts|2500}}\n|\n|1990\n|Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque is adjacent to the [[Shia]] [[seminary]] [[Alkauthar Islamic University|Al-Kauthar University]]. The iconic dome of this mosque is about 30 meters high from the ground level, and its 15 meters diameter makes the dome one of the largest in the country.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/mosque/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Jamia Masjid Umar Farooq]]\n|\n| [[Godhra, Karachi]], [[New Karachi]], [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n|\n|\n| 1973\n|\n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Kuzkandi Jamiah Masjid]]\n| [[Image:kuzkandimasjid.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Baghdada]], [[Mardan]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| \n| \n| 1950s\n| \n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad|Lal Masjid]] <br />(Red Mosque)\n| [[Image:Red Mosque Islamabad 1.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| \n| \n| 1965\n| The Lal Masjid, also known as the Red Mosque, was built in 1965 and is named for its red walls and interiors. The mosque is one of the oldest mosques in Islamabad.\n|<ref name=\"bbc030707\">{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6503477.stm| title = Profile: Islamabad's Red Mosque| publisher = BBC | date=July 3, 2007 | accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1345068|title=The legacy of Lal Masjid|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Mohabbat Khan Mosque]]\n| [[File:MKmosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Peshawar]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{nts|14000}}\n| {{convert|2800|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1670s\n| Mohabbat Khan Mosque is a 17th-century [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]-era mosque in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]]. The mosque was built between 1660 and 1670, and named after the Mughal governor of [[Peshawar]], Nawab [[Ali Mardan Khan|Mahabat Khan bin Ali Mardan Khan]].\n| <ref>{{cite journal|title=Mahabat Khan Mosque|journal=Pharos:Research Journal of the Shaykh Zayed Islamic Centre|date=1996|volume=3|issue=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PK_XAAAAMAAJ&q=khan+mosque+peshawar&dq=khan+mosque+peshawar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGvJfi_6XWAhXCRSYKHcsGCDo4FBDoAQglMAA|accessdate=15 September 2017|publisher=University of Peshawar}}</ref><ref name=dawn>{{cite news|title=AROUND TOWN: Masjid Mahabat Khan: Splendour of Mughal art|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/432286|accessdate=15 September 2017|agency=Dawn|date=5 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com.pk/search?rlz=1C1CHBF_enPK777PK777&ei=VLhhW9XHKKfjsAeG6aiYAg&q=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&oq=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&gs_l=psy-ab.3..33i21k1.524.5689.0.5830.28.18.1.0.0.0.366.2052.2-3j4.7.0....0...1.1.64.psy-ab..21.3.847...0j0i22i30k1j33i22i29i30k1.0.byi8EhNzChQ#lpqa=d,2|title=What is the capacity of the prayers that can be accommodated by the mosque?|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Qasim Ali Khan Mosque]]\n|[[File:Qasim Ali Khan Mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Peshawar]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| \n| \n| \n| Qasim Ali Khan Mosque was built in 1842. There is a myth that the mosque was constructed during the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] era.\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1190142|title=Facts and fiction surrounding the historic Masjid Qasim Ali Khan|last=Shinwari|first=Sher Alam|date=2015-06-24|work=Dawn|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Moti Masjid (Lahore)|Moti Masjid]]\n| [[File:Moti Mosque (inside Lahore Fort).JPG|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| {{convert|160|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1635 \n| Moti Masjid is a 17th-century [[religious]] [[building]] located inside the [[Lahore Fort]]. It is a small, [[white marble]] structure built by [[Mughal Empire|Mughal emperor]] [[Jahangir]], and is among his prominent extensions to the Lahore Fort Complex.\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Dar|first1=Nadeem|title=A pearl inside Lahore Fort \u2013 Moti Masjid|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2015/06/20/a-pearl-inside-lahore-fort-moti-masjid/|accessdate=6 January 2017|agency=Pakistan Today|date=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=2607 Lahore Fort Complex: Moti Masjid] {