onvert|3050|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1647\n| Shah Jahan Mosque is a 17th-century building that serves as the [[Jama Masjid|central mosque]] for the city of [[Thatta]], Sindh. It was built during the reign of [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Shah Jahan]].\n| <ref>{{cite book|last1=Sluglett|first1=Peter|title=Atlas of Islamic History|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317588979}}</ref><ref name=asher>{{cite book|last1=Asher|first1=Catherine|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|date=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521267281|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA349&dq=shah+jahan+thatta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq5L2T6Y7VAhWF7CYKHR3zA5YQ6AEIMjAC#v=snippet&q=thatta&f=false|accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discover-pakistan.com/shah-jahan-mosque.html|title=SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://visitpak.com/shah-jahan-mosque-or-shahjahani-mosque-thatta-sindh/|title=Shah Jahan Mosque, Thatta|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Shahi Eid Gah Mosque]]\n| [[File:Eidgah_mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Multan]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| {{convert|1250|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1735\n| Located on the main Multan-Lahore highway in the Northeast the city, the mosque is adjacent to the 20th century [[Sufi]] shrine of [[Ahmad Saeed Kazmi]].\n| <ref>{{cite book|last1=Yousaf|first1=Mohammad|title=A Brief History of Multan|date=1971|publisher=Ferozsons}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Shahi Mosque, Chitral]]\n| [[File:Shahi Mosque, Chitral.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Chitral]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{nts|20000}}\n| \n| 1924\n| It was the principal [[mosque]] of Chitral at the time of the existence of the [[Chitral (princely state)|State of Chitral]]. The mosque was built by [[Shuja ul-Mulk]] in 1924.\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Shahi Mosque, Chitral |url=https://www.croozi.com/shahi-masjid-chitral-kpk-pakistan |website=www.croozi.com |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Information on alamy.com |url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-shahi-masjid-chitral-built-in-1924-by-shujah-ul-mulk-then-the-mehta-116959865.html |website=www.alamy.com |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Built in 1924\">{{cite web|title=Built in 1924 by Shuja ul Mulk|url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-shahi-masjid-chitral-built-in-1924-by-shujah-ul-mulk-then-the-mehta-116959865.html|website=www.alamy.com|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mehtar of Chitral from 1895 to 1936 |url=http://www.dilkashpakistan.com/shahi-masjid-chitral-beautiful-pakistan/ |website=www.dilkashpakistan.com |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Sunehri Mosque, Lahore|Sunehri Mosque]]\n| [[File:Sunehri masjid top view 2.JPG|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|5000}}\n| {{convert|25948|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1753\n| Sunehri Mosque is located in the Kashmiri Bazaar of the [[Walled City of Lahore]]. The mosque was built in 1753 when the [[Mughal Empire]] was in decline.\n| <ref name=\"Sonehri Mosque\">{{cite news|title=Sonehri Mosque|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/mosque_sonehri.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|agency=Lahore Sites}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/mosque_sonehri.html|title=Sonehri Mosque|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Masjid e Tooba|Tooba Mosque]]\n|[[File:Tooba Mosque-44.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|5000}}\n| {{convert|3280|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1969\n| Masjid-e-Tooba was built in 1969 in [[Defence Housing Society, Karachi|Defence Housing Society]], Karachi. It is often claimed to be the largest single-dome mosque in the world.\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhatoday.com/masjid-e-tooba-all-you-need-to-know/|title=Masjid-e-Tooba \u2013 All You Need To Know!|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discover-pakistan.com/masjid-e-tooba.html|title=MASJID-E-TOOBA|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Wazir Khan Mosque]]\n| [[File:Wazir Khan Mosque by Moiz.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|10000}}\n| {{convert|3825|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1642\n| The mosque was commissioned during the reign of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] Emperor [[Shah Jahan]]. Construction of Wazir Khan Mosque began in 1634 [[Common era|C.E.]] and was completed in 1641.\n| <ref>{{cite news|title=Conservation of the Wazir Khan Mosque Lahore: Preliminary Report on Condition and Risk Assessment|url=http://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/6585/original/DPC3347.pdf?1384798179|accessdate=25 August 2016|agency=Aga Khan Development Network|date=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827000354/http://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/6585/original/DPC3347.pdf?1384798179|archive-date=27 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{cite web|title=Wazir Khan's Mosque, Lahore|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1278/|publisher=UNESCO| accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{commons category|Mosques in Pakistan}}\n{{Wiktionary|Mosque}}\n* [[Islam in Pakistan]]\n* [[Lists of mosques]]\n** [[Mosques of Lahore]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{List of mosques}}\n\n[[Category:Mosques in Pakistan| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of religious buildings and structures in Pakistan|Mosques]]\n[[Category:Lists of mosques|Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "Being an Islamic country, [[Pakistan]] is home to thousands of mosques. Some of the mosques are quite famous because of their size, beauty, architecture and history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakiholic.com/15-most-amazing-beautiful-mosques-pakistan/|title=15 Most Amazing and Beautiful Mosques in Pakistan|date=5 October 2016|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> The following is a '''list of [[mosque]]s in [[Pakistan]]'''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!class=unsortable|Images\n!City<!--Please 