 1614\n| Begum Shahi Mosque is an early 17th-century mosque situated in the [[Walled City of Lahore]]. The mosque was built between 1611 and 1614 during the reign of [[Mughal Emperor]] [[Jahangir]] in honor of his mother.\n|.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2016/03/12/begum-shahi-masjid/|title=Begum Shahi Masjid|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=asher/><ref name=TQ>{{cite news|title=Begum Shahi Masjid|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2016/03/12/features/begum-shahi-masjid/|accessdate=31 August 2016|agency=Pakistan Today|date=12 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gibb|first1=H. A. R.|title=The Encyclopaedia of Islam|date=1954|publisher=Brill Archive|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=apU3AAAAIAAJ&dq=maryam+zamani+mosque&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Bhong Mosque]]\n| [[File:BHONG_MOSQUE.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Rahim Yar Khan District]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| \n| 1982\n| Bhong Mosque was designed and constructed over a period of nearly 50 years (1932\u20131982) and won the [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]] in 1986.\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akdn.org/ky/architecture/project/bhong-mosque|title=Bhong Mosque|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pakistaniat.com/2009/07/27/architecture-pakistan-bhong-mosque/ |title=Architecture Pakistan: Bhong Mosque |access-date=2013-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711034957/http://pakistaniat.com/2009/07/27/architecture-pakistan-bhong-mosque/ |archive-date=2017-07-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.pakpost.gov.pk/philately/stamps2004/bhong_mousque.html Pakistan Post]</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Chaqchan Mosque]]\n| [[File:Side view of Chaqchan Mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Khaplu]], [[Gilgit Baltistan]]\n| {{nts|500}}\n| \n| 1370\n| The Kashmiri-style Chaqchan Mosque was built in 1370, shortly after the area\u2019s conversion to Islam.\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Two of the oldest mosques of Pakistan |url=http://blogs.dunyanews.tv/11753/ |website=Blogs.dunyanews.tv |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chaqchan Mosque, Khaplu |url=http://www.pakistanitourism.com/places-to-go/chaqchan-mosque |website=www.pakistantourism.com |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=baltistan in history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mQFuAAAAMAAJ&q=chaqchan+mosque&dq=chaqchan+mosque|author1=Afridi|first1=Banat Gul|year=1988}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[CMH Masjid Jhelum]]\n| [[File:CMH_Mosque.JPG|160px]]\n| [[Jhelum Cantt]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|25,000}}\n| \n| 1950\n|  Located at Jhelum Cantt, the foundation of CMH Mosque was laid by [[General]] Muhammad [[Ayub Khan (Field Marshal)|Ayub Khan]] on March 21, 1950 and opening ceremony was headed by [[Governor of Punjab (Pakistan)|Governor of Punjab]] [[Abdur Rab Nishtar|Sardar Abdur Rab Nishtar]].\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://jhelum.pk/jhelum-the-city-of-soldiers/|title=JHELUM- THE CITY OF SOLDIERS|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Dai Anga Mosque]]\n| [[File:The mosque view from the main entrance.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|\n| 1635 or 1639\n| Situated at the southeast of [[Lahore Railway Station]], in the city of [[Lahore]]. The mosque is said to have been built in 1635 in honour of the wetnurse of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] Emperor [[Shah Jahan]], [[Dai Anga]].\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Dai Anga Mosque|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/mosque_dai_anga.html|website=Lahore Sites of Interest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discover-pakistan.com/dai-anga-mosque.html|title=DAI ANGA MOSQUE - 1635|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Data Darbar]]\n|[[File:Data Durbar Mosque(2).jpg|160px]]\n|[[Lahore]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|52,000}}\n| {{convert|34200|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1978\n|Data Darbar, located in the city of [[Lahore]], is the largest [[Sufi]] shrine in [[South Asia]]. It was built to house the remains of the [[Sufi|Muslim mystic]], [[Ali Hujwiri|Abul Hassan Ali Hujwiri]], commonly known as ''Data Ganj Baksh''.\n|<ref name=a>{{cite book|last1=Halafoff|first1=Anna|last2=Clarke|first2=Matthew|title=Religion and Development in the Asia-Pacific: Sacred Places as Development Spaces|date=2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9781317647454|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cTslDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&dq=data+darbar+-bomb+-bombers+-suicide+-attack&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfwdy19J7WAhVMRyYKHQtzDDQQ6AEIWDAI#v=onepage&q=data%20darbar%20-bomb%20-bombers%20-suicide%20-attack&f=false|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"b\">{{cite book|last1=Quraeshi|first1=Samina|title=Sacred Spaces: A Journey with the Sufis of the Indus|date=2010|publisher=Peabody Museum Press|isbn=9780873658591|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yIrQkw9aN90C&pg=PA127&dq=data+ganj+-bomb+-bombers+-suicide+-attack&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVkaTN957WAhWRdSYKHTX9C-UQ6AEITDAI#v=onepage&q=data%20ganj%20-bomb%20-bombers%20-suicide%20-attack&f=false|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakpedia.pk/data-darbar-complex|title=Data Darbar Complex|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Faisal Mosque]]\n| [[File:Shah Faisal Masjid, Islamabad.JPG|160px]]\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| {{nts|100,000}}\n| {{convert|5000|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1986\n| Faisal Mosque is the national mosque of Pakistan and is named after [[Faisal of Saudi Arabia|Saudi King Faisal]]. It can hold 100,000 worshippers, while the surrounding porticoes and the courtyard up-to 200,000 more.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/pakistan/islamabad-faisal-mosque|title=Faisal Mosque - Islamabad, Pakistan|website=www.sacred-destinations.com|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.houseofpakistan.com/2015/11/king-of-all-mosques-faisal-mosque/|title=KING OF ALL MOSQUES \u2013 FAISAL MOSQUE|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Dawat-e-Islami|Faizan-e-Madinah]]\n|[[File:Mosque And Education Center Run By Dawat-e-Islami.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|20,000}}\n| {{convert|10000|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1999\n|A Mosque and education center run by [[Dawat-e-Islami]]. One of the largest mosques in Pakistan covering over 10,000 m<sup>2</sup> with a capacity of over 20,000.\n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Grand Jamia Mosque, Karachi]]\n| \n| [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|800,000}}\n| {{convert|202343|m2|abbr=on}}\n| Under construction\n| Grand Jamia Mosque, also known as Bahria Town Jamia Masjid Complex, is an under-construction [[Cultural center|cultural]] complex. When completed, the complex will include the world's third largest [[mosque]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/business/07-Jan-2015/groundbreaking-ceremony-of-grand-jamia-masjid|title=Groundbreaking ceremony|date=7 January 2015|work=The Nation|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/817839/bahria-breaks-ground-on-worlds-3rd-largest-mosque/|title=Bahria breaks ground on world's 3rd largest mosque|date=7 January 2015|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/Pakistan/253767-Karachi-Foundation-stone-of-worlds-3rd-largest-m|title=Karachi: Foundation stone of world's 3rd largest mosque laid  - Pakistan - Dunya News|work=dunyanews.tv|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Grand Mosque Allahabad]]\n| [[File:GMA Outside hall front view.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Naushahro Feroze District]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|10,000}}\n| {{convert|7400|m2|abbr=on}}\n| Under construction\n| Grand Mosque Allahabad is located in [[Kandiaro]], [[Sindh]].\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Mosque, Allahabad |url=http://www.islahulmuslimeen.org/grand-mosque-allahabad |website=www.islahulmuslimeen.org |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref> \n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Grand Jamia Mosque, Lahore]]\n| [[File:Grand_Jamia_Masjid_Bahria_Town_Lahore_Pakistan_cropped.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|100,000}}\n| \n| 2014\n| Seventh largest mosque in the world, and the largest in Pakistan in terms of surface area. It can accommodate 25,000 worshipers indoors, while the courtyard and corridor leading to the main halls of worship can accommodate a total of 70,000.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-10-12/news/54928831_1_mosque-multan-pakistan|title=Pakistan's third largest mosque,|work=timesofindia-economictimes|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/775536/unparalleled-achievement-zardari-inaugurates-pakistans-largest-mosque/|title=Unparalleled achievement: Zardari inaugurates Pakistan\u2019s largest mosque|date=15 October 2014|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beautifulmosque.com/grand-jamia-mosque-in-lahore-pakistan|title=Beautiful Mosque Pictures|website=www.beautifulmosque.com|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| Jamia Masjid Banbhore\n|[[File:Floor of the Jamia Masjid Banbhore dating back 727 AD.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Thatta]], [[Sindh]]\n| \n| \n| 727 AD\n| [[Banbhore]] is an ancient city dating to the 1st century BC located in [[Sindh]], Pakistan. The eastern part of the city contains ruins of Banbhore Mosque with an inscription dating to 727 AD, sixteen years after the conquest of Sindh, indicating the best-preserved example of the earliest mosques in the region. Ruins are still preserved in the city.\n|<ref name=Wesler>{{cite book|title=An Archaeology of Religion|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0761858454|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qSExw3tH1oC&pg=PA253|author=Kit W. Wesler|accessdate=8 September 2012|page=253|date=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Mosque of Banbhore|url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=14204|publisher=ArchNet|accessdate=8 September 2012|quote=... the Jami' Masjid of Banbhore is one of the earliest known mosques in the Indo-Pakistan subcontinent.}}</ref><ref name=Sindh>{{cite web|title=Banbhore Museum|url=http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|work=Culture Department|publisher=Govt. of Sindh|accessdate=3 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108165854/http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Mosque (Khudabad)]]\n|[[File:Main building of Jamia Masjid Khudabad.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Dadu District]], [[Sindh]]\n|{{nts|5000}}\n|\n|1700 - 1718\n| The mosque is situated in [[Khudabad]] in [[Dadu District]] and was built during the reign of [[Yar Muhammad Kalhoro]] between 1700 and 1718.\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamia Mosque (Khudabad) in Dadu District |url=https://www.sindhidunya.com/khudabad-mosque-antique-heritage-sindh/ |website=www.sindhidunya.com |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque|Jamia Al-Kauthar]]\n|[[File:Jamia Al Kauthar Mosque.png|160px]]\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|{{nts|2500}}\n|\n|1990\n|Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque is adjacent to the [[Shia]] [[seminary]] [[Alkauthar Islamic University|Al-Kauthar University]]. The iconic dome of this mosque is about 30 meters high from the ground level, and its 15 meters diameter makes the dome one of the largest in the country.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/mosque/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Jamia Masjid Umar Farooq]]\n|\n| [[Godhra, Karachi]], [[New Karachi]], [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n|\n|\n| 1973\n|\n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Kuzkandi Jamiah Masjid]]\n| [[Image:kuzkandimasjid.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Baghdada]], [[Mardan]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| \n| \n| 1950s\n| \n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad|Lal Masjid]] <br />(Red Mosque)\n| [[Image:Red Mosque Islamabad 1.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| \n| \n| 1965\n| The Lal Masjid, also known as the Red Mosque, was built in 1965 and is named for its red walls and interiors. The mosque is one of the oldest mosques in Islamabad.\n|<ref name=\"bbc030707\">{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6503477.stm| title = Profile: Islamabad's Red Mosque| publisher = BBC | date=July 3, 2007 | accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1345068|title=The legacy of Lal Masjid|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Mohabbat Khan Mosque]]\n| [[File:MKmosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Peshawar]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{nts|14000}}\n| {{convert|2800|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1670s\n| Mohabbat Khan Mosque is a 17th-century [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]-era mosque in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]]. The mosque was built between 1660 and 1670, and named after the Mughal governor of [[Peshawar]], Nawab [[Ali Mardan Khan|Mahabat Khan bin Ali Mardan Khan]].\n| <ref>{{cite journal|title=Mahabat Khan Mosque|journal=Pharos:Research Journal of the Shaykh Zayed Islamic Centre|date=1996|volume=3|issue=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PK_XAAAAMAAJ&q=khan+mosque+peshawar&dq=khan+mosque+peshawar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGvJfi_6XWAhXCRSYKHcsGCDo4FBDoAQglMAA|accessdate=15 September 2017|publisher=University of Peshawar}}</ref><ref name=dawn>{{cite news|title=AROUND TOWN: Masjid Mahabat Khan: Splendour of Mughal art|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/432286|accessdate=15 September 2017|agency=Dawn|date=5 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com.pk/search?rlz=1C1CHBF_enPK777PK777&ei=VLhhW9XHKKfjsAeG6aiYAg&q=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&oq=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&gs_l=psy-ab.3..33i21k1.524.5689.0.5830.28.18.1.0.0.0.366.2052.2-3j4.7.0....0...1.1.64.psy-ab..21.3.847...0j0i22i30k1j33i22i29i30k1.0.byi8EhNzChQ#lpqa=d,2|